content:
The chunk is part of a comprehensive guide on configuring particle systems in Panda3D. It focuses on the "Emitter" section, detailing how emitters determine particle emission parameters. The content explains the role of emitters, lists available types such as ArcEmitter and SphereVolumeEmitter, notes that each emitter type is declared in separate .h files, and provides a code example demonstrating setup using SphereVolumeEmitter with specific configurations like emission type and radius. This section is crucial for users needing to customize particle behavior based on different emitter shapes and settings.

Emitter

The emitter is used to emit the particles generated by the factory. The shape of the emitter determins the initial position and motion direction of the particles.

Available Emitters

.ArcEmitter

.BoxEmitter

.DiscEmitter

.LineEmitter

.RectangleEmitter

.RingEmitter

.SphereSurfaceEmitter

.SphereVolumeEmitter

.TangentRingEmitter

Each emitter is declared in a separate .h file with the same name as the emitter. For example: ArcEmitter is declared in arcEmitter.h

PT(SphereVolumeEmitter) sphere_emitter = new SphereVolumeEmitter;
sphere_emitter->set_emission_type(SphereVolumeEmitter::ET_RADIATE);
sphere_emitter->set_radius(3.0);
// negative values emit the particles toward the sphere center
sphere_emitter->set_amplitude(1);
sphere_emitter->set_amplitude_spread(0);
sphere_emitter->set_offset_force(LVector3(0, 0, 0));
sphere_emitter->set_explicit_launch_vector(LVector3(1, 0, 0));
sphere_emitter->set_radiate_origin(LPoint3(0, 0, 0));

